name: Brown et al 2011 Purkinje Biochem-Electrophysiol SCA
annot:
This is the PPR Model, a simplified model of the cerebellar Purkinje neuron that combines electrophysiology with detailed biochemistry. This model accompanies the 2010 manuscript entitled "Virtual NEURON: a Strategy For Merged Biochemical and Electrophysiological Modeling" by Sherry-Ann Brown, Ion Moraru, James Schaff, and Leslie M. Loew.

The PPR model developed in NEURON can be accessed in ModelDb (http://senselab.med.yale.edu/ModelDb/) by searching for the authors. 

Compartment mapping to manuscript description in Figure 1b:

i - soma
ii - maindendite
iii - smoothdistaldendriteshort
iv - smoothdistaldendritelong
v - spinydistaldendrite
vi - adjacentdendrite
vii - spine
viii - IO1smoooth
ix - IO1spiny
x - IO2smooth
xi - IO2spiny
xii - IO3smooth
xiii - IO3spiny
xiv - IO4smooth
xv - IO4spiny
xvi - IO5spiny
xvii - IO6spiny

name: Brown et al 2011 Analysis of SCA15-SCA16 with IC4 Peptide Application
annot:
cloned from 'Brown et al 2010 Analysis of SCA15-SCA16 with IC4 Peptide Application' owned by user Sensation
Goals:
1. Create a simple model that: 
a. explains increased sensitivity of IP3R1 for IP3 when the IP3R1 C-terminal tail is bound by mutant huntingtin/ataxin-1/ataxin-2/ataxin-3, as in SCA1, SCA2, SCA3, and HD.
b. describes a mechanism for the neuroprotective effect (specifically via normalized calcium release) of an IP3R1 C-terminal peptide in HD.
c. predicts whether ICpeptide treatment in SCA1, SCA2, and SC3 can normalize calcium release, as in HD.
d. predicts whether ICpeptide treatment in SCA15 and SCA16 can normalize calcium release, by increasing IP3R1 sensitivity to IP3.
e. illustrates that the same ICpeptide can have opposite effects on the net sensitivity of IP3R1 for IP3, and resulting calcium release in SCA1/SCA2/SCA3/HD versus SCA15/SCA16.

Assumptions:
1. Affinity of IP3R1 C-terminal tip (ICt) is greater for mutant proteins (mAtaxin1, mAtaxin2, mAtaxin3, mHuntingtin) than for Protein Phosphatase 1 alpah (PP1a).
2. Affinity of ICpeptide (IC1, IC4, IC10, etc) for mutant proteins and PP1a is greater than the affinity of ICt for the mutant proteins and the phosphatase. This assumption is based on the fact that the ICpeptide is soluble/mobile/freely diffusing, whereas ICt is fixed in the SER membrnae, and is therefore immobile and does not freely diffuse.
3. Affinity of IP3R1 for its ligand, IP3, is proportional to the amount of PP1a-bound ICt.

Predictions:
1. The same ICpeptide may be used as a therapeutic tool for treating various IP3R1-associated ataxias (ataxias in which IP3R1 is less abundant or more sensitive than in wild type mice or unaffected individuals): e.g., SCA1, SCA2, SCA3, HD, SCA15, and SCA16.
2. Treating SCA1, SCA2, and SCA3 mice or individuals with ICpeptide can normalize calcium release, by restoring normal (i.e., decreasing to normal values the) sensitivity of IP3R1 for IP3.
3. Treating SCA15 and SCA16 mice or individuals with ICpeptide can normalize calcium release, by increasing the sensitivity of IP3R1 for its ligand, IP3, in the context of reduced abundance of IP3R1.
4. Various concentrations of ICpeptide will be needed to increase IP3R1 sensitivity in SCA15 and SCA16, based on the levels of reduced abundance.
5. Various concentrations of ICpeptide will be needed to normalize IP3R1 sensitivity and consequently calcium release in SCA1, SCA2, and SCA3, based on the degrees to which IP3R1 sensitivity to IP3 is pathologically increased (dependent on concentration of mutant protein).
6. Greater concentrations of ICpeptide will be needed for SCA1, SCA2, and SCA3 than for SCA15 and SCA16.
7. Relative concentrations of mutant proteins and phosphatase...

Peptides:
IC4 - Q2714-A2749 - specific for PP1alpha
IC10 - F2627-A2749 - HD and PP1alpha

name: Brown et al 2011 Analysis of SCA1-SCA2-SCA3 with IC-G2736X Peptide
annot:
cloned from 'Brown et al 2010 Analysis of SCA1-SCA2-SCA3 with IC-G2736X Peptide Application' owned by user Sensation
Goals:
1. Create a simple model that: 
a. explains increased sensitivity of IP3R1 for IP3 when the IP3R1 C-terminal tail is bound by mutant huntingtin/ataxin-1/ataxin-2/ataxin-3, as in SCA1, SCA2, SCA3, and HD.
b. describes a mechanism for the neuroprotective effect (specifically via normalized calcium release) of an IP3R1 C-terminal peptide in HD.
c. predicts whether ICpeptide treatment in SCA1, SCA2, and SC3 can normalize calcium release, as in HD.
d. predicts whether ICpeptide treatment in SCA15 and SCA16 can normalize calcium release, by increasing IP3R1 sensitivity to IP3.
e. illustrates that the same ICpeptide can have opposite effects on the net sensitivity of IP3R1 for IP3, and resulting calcium release in SCA1/SCA2/SCA3/HD versus SCA15/SCA16.

Assumptions:
1. Affinity of IP3R1 C-terminal tip (ICt) is greater for mutant proteins (mAtaxin1, mAtaxin2, mAtaxin3, mHuntingtin) than for Protein Phosphatase 1 alpah (PP1a).
2. Affinity of ICpeptide (IC1, IC4, IC10, etc) for mutant proteins and PP1a is greater than the affinity of ICt for the mutant proteins and the phosphatase. This assumption is based on the fact that the ICpeptide is soluble/mobile/freely diffusing, whereas ICt is fixed in the SER membrnae, and is therefore immobile and does not freely diffuse.
3. Affinity of IP3R1 for its ligand, IP3, is proportional to the amount of PP1a-bound ICt.

Predictions:
1. The same ICpeptide may be used as a therapeutic tool for treating various IP3R1-associated ataxias (ataxias in which IP3R1 is less abundant or more sensitive than in wild type mice or unaffected individuals): e.g., SCA1, SCA2, SCA3, HD, SCA15, and SCA16.
2. Treating SCA1, SCA2, and SCA3 mice or individuals with ICpeptide can normalize calcium release, by restoring normal (i.e., decreasing to normal values the) sensitivity of IP3R1 for IP3.
3. Treating SCA15 and SCA16 mice or individuals with ICpeptide can normalize calcium release, by increasing the sensitivity of IP3R1 for its ligand, IP3, in the context of reduced abundance of IP3R1.
4. Various concentrations of ICpeptide will be needed to increase IP3R1 sensitivity in SCA15 and SCA16, based on the levels of reduced abundance.
5. Various concentrations of ICpeptide will be needed to normalize IP3R1 sensitivity and consequently calcium release in SCA1, SCA2, and SCA3, based on the degrees to which IP3R1 sensitivity to IP3 is pathologically increased (dependent on concentration of mutant protein).
6. Greater concentrations of ICpeptide will be needed for SCA1, SCA2, and SCA3 than for SCA15 and SCA16.
7. Relative concentrations of mutant proteins and phosphatase...

Peptides:
IC4 - Q2714-A2749 - specific for PP1alpha
IC10 - F2627-A2749 - HD and PP1alpha
IC-G2736X - D2590-G2736 - specific for HD

name: Brown et al 2011 Purkinje 3D Spine - Spinocerebellar Ataxia study
annot:
cloned from 'Brown et al 2010 3D spine' owned by user Sensation
Clusters at PSD: 2x, 4x, 10x global concentration


Distribution within PSD:-

Reasoning 1. Molecules (receptors,R and ion channels,IC) homogenously expressed in PSD: high concentration, small space between PSD and SER enough to localize activity.

Lateral: mGLUR/PLC activation/IP3 pulses, AMPAR, Voltage-gated calcium channels
Central: mGLUR/PLC activation/IP3 pulses, AMPAR, Voltage-gated calcium channels

Reasoning 2. All ion channels at central PSD; signalling receptors at lateral PSD: immediate changes in electrophysiology that will take time to propagate to the soma. Immediate depolarization will then open VGCC allowing calcium to rush into the PSD compartment. This calcium diffuses to the lateral PSD, where it binds IP3R1, synergizing calcium release from the SER. BK channles in the central PSD can 'immediately' turn off the calcium influx. Having BK channels in the central PSD allows for immediate activation of BK by calcium, without depending on diffusion into the lateral PSD.

Lateral: mGLUR/PLC activation/IP3 pulses
Central: AMPAR, Voltage-gated ion channels

Reasoning 3. Signalling molecules at the lateral PSD, AMPAR and VGCCs at the central PSD, BK at the lateral PSD: ...calcium can diffuse from the central PSD into the lateral PSD to facilitiate activation of BK by IP3R1-mediated calcium as well (or calcium flux from the SER as well).

Lateral: mGLUR/PLC activation/IP3 pulses, BK channel
Central: AMPAR, Voltage-gated calcium channels

Reasoning 4. AMPAR at the central PSD, signalling molecules and all voltage-gated channels at the lateral PSD: Depolarization...spreads quickly to the lateral PSD, activates calcium in close proximity (perhaps physically tethered next to the BK channels).

Lateral: mGLUR/PLC activation/IP3 pulses, Voltage-gated ion channels
Central: AMPAR

Note that: 
a. if Homer 3 is enriched at the lateral PSD, then mGluR activaty and IP3R1 activity may be enriched at the lateral PSD.
b. calcium rushing in from outside the cell may give greater concentration than calcium released from the ER. So more calcium from outside can diffuse to lateral PSD to meet BK channels there.)
c. the calcium ATPase (drive pump) may localize in signaling complexes with mGluR and IP3R1!



CHANGE PIP2 BOUND AND SINK IN ALL MODELS WHERE I DO NOT RETAIN THE DEFAULT INITIAL VALUES.

name: Brown et al 2011 Analysis of SCA15-SCA16 with IC4 Peptide Application
annot:
cloned from 'Brown et al 2010 Analysis of SCA15-SCA16 with IC4 Peptide Application' owned by user Sensation
Goals:
1. Create a simple model that: 
a. explains increased sensitivity of IP3R1 for IP3 when the IP3R1 C-terminal tail is bound by mutant huntingtin/ataxin-1/ataxin-2/ataxin-3, as in SCA1, SCA2, SCA3, and HD.
b. describes a mechanism for the neuroprotective effect (specifically via normalized calcium release) of an IP3R1 C-terminal peptide in HD.
c. predicts whether ICpeptide treatment in SCA1, SCA2, and SC3 can normalize calcium release, as in HD.
d. predicts whether ICpeptide treatment in SCA15 and SCA16 can normalize calcium release, by increasing IP3R1 sensitivity to IP3.
e. illustrates that the same ICpeptide can have opposite effects on the net sensitivity of IP3R1 for IP3, and resulting calcium release in SCA1/SCA2/SCA3/HD versus SCA15/SCA16.

Assumptions:
1. Affinity of IP3R1 C-terminal tip (ICt) is greater for mutant proteins (mAtaxin1, mAtaxin2, mAtaxin3, mHuntingtin) than for Protein Phosphatase 1 alpah (PP1a).
2. Affinity of ICpeptide (IC1, IC4, IC10, etc) for mutant proteins and PP1a is greater than the affinity of ICt for the mutant proteins and the phosphatase. This assumption is based on the fact that the ICpeptide is soluble/mobile/freely diffusing, whereas ICt is fixed in the SER membrnae, and is therefore immobile and does not freely diffuse.
3. Affinity of IP3R1 for its ligand, IP3, is proportional to the amount of PP1a-bound ICt.

Predictions:
1. The same ICpeptide may be used as a therapeutic tool for treating various IP3R1-associated ataxias (ataxias in which IP3R1 is less abundant or more sensitive than in wild type mice or unaffected individuals): e.g., SCA1, SCA2, SCA3, HD, SCA15, and SCA16.
2. Treating SCA1, SCA2, and SCA3 mice or individuals with ICpeptide can normalize calcium release, by restoring normal (i.e., decreasing to normal values the) sensitivity of IP3R1 for IP3.
3. Treating SCA15 and SCA16 mice or individuals with ICpeptide can normalize calcium release, by increasing the sensitivity of IP3R1 for its ligand, IP3, in the context of reduced abundance of IP3R1.
4. Various concentrations of ICpeptide will be needed to increase IP3R1 sensitivity in SCA15 and SCA16, based on the levels of reduced abundance.
5. Various concentrations of ICpeptide will be needed to normalize IP3R1 sensitivity and consequently calcium release in SCA1, SCA2, and SCA3, based on the degrees to which IP3R1 sensitivity to IP3 is pathologically increased (dependent on concentration of mutant protein).
6. Greater concentrations of ICpeptide will be needed for SCA1, SCA2, and SCA3 than for SCA15 and SCA16.
7. Relative concentrations of mutant proteins and phosphatase...

Peptides:
IC4 - Q2714-A2749 - specific for PP1alpha
IC10 - F2627-A2749 - HD and PP1alpha

name: Brown et al 2008 PIP2 Diffusion 1D and 3D
annot: 1D and 3D models (1 physiological biomodel with several applications determined by respective geometries and parameters) for PIP2 Diffusion along a spiny Purkinje dendrite. 1D model geometry uses half of 300um long dendritic branch, represented by a 150um long straight line. Thus, a small length representing half of a dendritic segment spanning the stimulated spine is used for the constructed geometry (0.5 * (1/14 = 0.02714) = 0.0367) and for the experimentally derived geometry (0.5 * (1/11 = 0.0909) = 0.0454). Brown et al 2008 Biophysical Journal

name: Brown et al 2008 Purkinje 1D
annot: 1D models (1 physiological biomodel with two different applications determined by the length of dendritic segment spanning the stimulated spine in respective 3D geometries) for PIP2 concentration changes with stimulated synthesis and lateral diffusion of PIP2. The 1D model geometry uses half of 300um long dendritic branch, represented by a 150um long straight line. Thus, a small length representing half of a dendritic segment spanning the stimulated spine is used for the constructed geometry (0.5 * (1/14 = 0.02714) = 0.0367) and for the experimentally derived geometry (0.5 * (1/11 = 0.0909) = 0.0454). Brown et al 2008 Biophysical Journal

name: Morris-Lecar Mutual Inhibition
annot: Demonstrates how fast inhibition leads to antiphase behavior (for t<0.8s, beta=1000/s) and slow inhibition leads to in-phase behavior (for t>0.8s, beta=100/s). SurfToVol_PlasmaMembrane1 and SurfToVol_PlasmaMembrane2 were changed to 1806 to cancel out KMOLE in the equations for s1 and s2 kinetics. Described in 6.3 and illustrated in Figure 6.7.

name: Morris-Lecar Mutual Excitation
annot: Demonstrates how fast excitatory synapses lead to synchrony and slow excitatory synapses lead to asynchrony in two identical electrically coupled cells. The only parameter modified is beta (=1000/s in Figure 6.6A and =100/s in Figure 6.6C). Described in 6.3.

name: Keizer-Levine Open-Cell
annot: Models Ca2+ oscillations in bullfrog sympathetic ganglion neurons via RyR channel kinetics. Described in 5.2.3 and illustrated in Figure 5.8.

name: L-Type Calcium Channels
annot: Models L-type Ca2+ channel kinetics in the Aplysia neuron. Used to demonstrate the rapid equilibrium approximation. Described in 4.1 and illustrated in Figure 4.3.

name: Morris-Lecar Coincidence Detection
annot: Demonstrates coincidence detection for excitatory inputs. Described in 6.4 and illustrated in Figure 6.9.

name: Chay-Keizer ER
annot: Models pancreatic beta-cell bursting. Described in 5.4 and illustrated in Figure 5.21.

name: Hodgkin-Huxley
annot: Models electrical behavior of the squid giant axon. Used to demonstrate interacting ion channels. Described in 2.5.

name: Morris-Lecar Type II
annot: Models electrical behavior of barnacle muscle fiber. Used to demonstrate interacting ion channels. Described in 2.4.
